wBox=\"0 0 20 20\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" stroke=\"var(--color-fg-primary)\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\"><g><title></title><path d=\"M2.53001 7.81595C3.49179 4.73911 6.43281 2.5 9.91173 2.5C13.1684 2.5 15.9537 4.46214 17.0852 7.23684L17.6179 8.67647M17.6179 8.67647L18.5002 4.26471M17.6179 8.67647L13.6473 6.91176M17.4995 12.1841C16.5378 15.2609 13.5967 17.5 10.1178 17.5C6.86118 17.5 4.07589 15.5379 2.94432 12.7632L2.41165 11.3235M2.41165 11.3235L1.5293 15.7353M2.41165 11.3235L6.38224 13.0882\"></path></g></svg></button><button tabindex=\"0\" type=\"button\" class=\"pencraft pc-reset pencraft icon-container view-image\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" class=\"lucide lucide-maximize2 lucide-maximize-2\"><polyline points=\"15 3 21 3 21 9\"></polyline><polyline points=\"9 21 3 21 3 15\"></polyline><line x1=\"21\" x2=\"14\" y1=\"3\" y2=\"10\"></line><line x1=\"3\" x2=\"10\" y1=\"21\" y2=\"14\"></li",
  "content_text": "Christmas breaks my routine, overloads my senses, and reactivates old stuff I thought I\u2019d dealt with. This is how I get through it without burning out. Christmas is not one day for me. It\u2019s weeks of noise, interruptions, and expectations I didn\u2019t agree to. For a long time, I told myself I\u2019d \u201ccope better this year\u201d. I never did. What helped wasn\u2019t trying harder. It was preparing honestly. I stopped pretending Christmas would feel calm. And started planning like it wouldn\u2019t. That one shift changed everything. I expect my routine to break. I expect my nervous system to be jumpy. I expect old family dynamics to make a surprise appearance. Not because I\u2019m negative. Because I\u2019m realistic. So I decide things early. How long I\u2019m staying. What I\u2019m skipping. When I\u2019m leaving. I don\u2019t make those choices in the moment. I make them while my brain is still on my side. On the day itself, I keep it simple. I eat before hunger turns into irritation. I take breaks before I\u2019m overwhelmed. I step outside without explaining myself. I leave early without apologising. I don\u2019t push through discomfort to be polite. Politeness is expensive. And when I do get triggered \u2014 because I do \u2014 I don\u2019t argue with my nervous system. I pause. I ground. I don\u2019t pile shame on top of stress. Then, when it\u2019s over, I rest. On purpose. No replaying conversations. No big decisions. No self-interrogation. Recovery is part of Christmas too. I don\u2019t aim to enjoy every moment. I aim to survive it intact. If Christmas feels like this for you too, I\u2019ve put everything I use into a short, free Google Doc. No hype. No fixing. Just what helps. You\u2019ll find the free Christmas survival doc linked below. And if nothing else, let this be enough: You\u2019re not doing Christmas wrong. You\u2019re just doing it with a nervous system that notices everything. That\u2019s how I prepare for two weeks of overstimulation, lack of routine, and too many triggers. Christmas. How I survive Christmas as a neurodivergent adult 1 1 Share Previous",
